The bugzilla importer scans comments for links to bug ids so we can create links to the newly created jira issues. 

However this can fail causing the entire import to fail. We had a customer whose bugzilla data had a comment "luck Bug 7777777777777...". We try to convert the 7777... to an integer, but it threw a number format exception because it is outside the rage of an Integer. 

The code in question is in BugzillaImportBean#rewriteBugLinkInText:

{code:java}public void appendSubstitution(StringBuffer appendBuffer, MatchResult match,
                                           int substitutionCount,
                                           PatternMatcherInput originalInput,
                                           PatternMatcher matcher, Pattern pattern)
            {
                String bugId = match.group(1);
                Long jiraIssueId = (Long) importedKeys.get(new Integer(bugId)); // this is where it blows up
                if (jiraIssueId == null)
                {
                    log("No imported issue found for bug reference " + bugId + " in " + parentIssueKey);
                    appendBuffer.append(originalInput);
                } 
{code}

We should check the bug id will actually fit into an Integer and fail in a similar manner to the case were a jira issue isn't found.

When you have a lucene query such as:
bq. {{-version:-1}}
or
bq. {{-nonemptyfieldids:version}}
You need to supplement it with the visibility query on the field, like this:
bq. {{-nonemptyfieldids:version +visiblefieldids:version}}

When the field "version" is not visible and in scope of an issue, it will not be indexed. This means that positive queries like {{version:10000}} correctly skip the issue in question (despite the field's value). However, a negative query like {{-version:10000}} will return those issues which do not have version indexed, which is not what we want when we turn off indexing of a field for a particular issue. (For a more concrete example see JRA-17904)

So to counteract this, we need to supplement these queries with the visibility query, so that we exclude the non-indexed-for-field issues as well as the ones which have a specific value. The same goes for {{-nonemptyfieldids:version}}; when {{version}} is not indexed, it does not appear in the list of non empty field ids, regardless of empty-ness.

